questions.scenario:
You are debugging a production issue in a Spring Boot application. A developer has implemented a `PaymentService` where an outer transaction should survive a failure in a non-critical auditing task. However, logs show that when `auditTransaction()` fails, the entire transaction is rolled back despite the `try-catch` block. 

java
@Service
public class PaymentService {
    @Transactional
    public void processPayment(Payment p) {
        savePayment(p);
        try {
            this.auditTransaction(p);
        } catch (Exception e) {
            log.error("Audit failed but continuing payment");
        }
    }

    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
    public void auditTransaction(Payment p) {
        throw new RuntimeException("Audit DB Down");
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue where a reactive Netty-based Spring Cloud Gateway is leaking memory and intermittently hanging. You find that a custom `GlobalFilter` has a generic catch block meant to handle all errors during request signing. 

java
public Mono<Void> filter(ServerWebExchange exchange, GatewayFilterChain chain) {
    try {
        return chain.filter(exchange);
    } catch (Exception e) {
        return handleFailure(exchange);
    }
}

However, logs show that certain fatal issues, like `OutOfMemoryError` or `StackOverflowError`, are bypassing this block and causing the thread to die silently.
